        {
          "name": "Edge Case - Update Non-existent Post 999",
          "request": {
            "method": "PUT",
            "header": [
              {
                "key": "Content-Type",
                "value": "application/json"
              }
            ],
            "body": {
              "mode": "raw",
              "raw": "{\n  \"title\": \"Ghost Post\",\n  \"body\": \"This post does not exist\",\n  \"userId\": 1\n}"
            },
            "url": {
              "raw": "https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts/999",
              "protocol": "https",
              "host": ["jsonplaceholder", "typicode", "com"],
              "path": ["posts", "999"]
            },
            "description": "## Request Details\n- **Method:** PUT\n- **Endpoint:** /posts/999\n- **Path Parameter:** id = 999 (does not exist)\n- **Headers:** Content-Type: application/json\n- **Body:** { title, body, userId }\n\n## Expected Response\n- **Status Code:** 500 Internal Server Error\n- **Body:** Error response\n\n## Analysis\nNegative test: attempting to update a resource that does not exist. JSONPlaceholder returns 500 Internal Server Error for PUT on non-existent IDs beyond its dataset. A well-designed production API should return 404 Not Found instead. The 500 response indicates the mock server does not gracefully handle this edge case — it throws an unhandled error rather than returning a proper 404. This is a notable behavioral difference from REST best practices."
          },
          "response": [
            {
              "name": "500 - Internal Server Error for Non-existent Resource",
              "originalRequest": {
                "method": "PUT",
                "header": [
                  { "key": "Content-Type", "value": "application/json" }
